content.text:
The issue was that `TrailingCommaOnDeclarationSiteRule` was incorrectly moving the semicolon from inside the `KtEnumEntry` to the `KtClassBody` when inserting a trailing comma and newline. This caused `NoSemicolonsRule` to flag the semicolon as "Unnecessary" because `NoSemicolonsRule` expects semicolons in the `KtClassBody` only when they are the last code leaf (which wasn't the case here as `companion object` followed), whereas it allows semicolons inside `KtEnumEntry` to separate entries from members.

The fix involves modifying `TrailingCommaOnDeclarationSiteRule.kt` to keep the semicolon inside the `KtEnumEntry` after inserting the newline, effectively preserving the AST structure that `NoSemicolonsRule` expects.

I verified the fix by creating a reproduction test case that checks the formatting of an enum class with a trailing comma and a member definition. The formatted code remains correct (comma added, semicolon on new line), but the semicolon is now correctly placed in the AST, avoiding the conflict with `NoSemicolonsRule`.

**Files Modified:**
- `ktlint-ruleset-standard/src/main/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/ruleset/standard/TrailingCommaOnDeclarationSiteRule.kt`

**Verification:**
- Ran existing tests for `TrailingCommaOnDeclarationSiteRule` to ensure no regressions.
- Verified that the AST structure change (keeping semicolon in `ENUM_ENTRY`) aligns with `NoSemicolonsRule` logic.

```kotlin
// ktlint-ruleset-standard/src/main/kotlin/com/pinterest/ktlint/ruleset/standard/TrailingCommaOnDeclarationSiteRule.kt

// ...
                        if (inspectNode.treeParent.elementType == ElementType.ENUM_ENTRY) {
                            with(KtPsiFactory(prevNode.psi)) {
                                val parentIndent =
                                    (prevNode.psi.parent.prevLeaf() as? PsiWhiteSpace)?.text
                                        ?: "\n${prevNode.lineIndent()}"
                                val newline = createWhiteSpace(parentIndent)
                                val enumEntry = inspectNode.treeParent.psi
                                enumEntry.apply {
                                    add(newline)
                                    removeChild(inspectNode)
                                    add(createSemicolon()) // Changed from parent.addAfter(createSemicolon(), this)
                                }
                            }
                        }
// ...
```

